(770,6,'OpenAI Fellows Fall 2018','We’re now accepting applications for the next cohort of OpenAI Fellows, a program which offers a compensated 6-month apprenticeship in AI research at OpenAI.','https://openai.com/index/openai-fellows','','2026-01-31 11:04:39','{\"raw_item\":\"<item>\\n            <title><![CDATA[OpenAI Fellows Fall 2018]]><\\/title>\\n            <description><![CDATA[We\\u2019re now accepting applications for the next cohort of OpenAI Fellows, a program which offers a compensated 6-month apprenticeship in AI research at OpenAI.]]><\\/description>\\n            <link>https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/openai-fellows<\\/link>\\n            <guid isPermaLink=\\\"true\\\">https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/openai-fellows<\\/guid>\\n            <category><![CDATA[Company]]><\\/category>\\n            <pubDate>Wed, 30 May 2018 07:00:00 GMT<\\/pubDate>\\n        <\\/item>\",\"source_name\":\"OpenAI Blog\"}',48.00,NULL,0.00,0,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'2026-01-31 10:47:37','2026-01-31 11:04:39'),
(771,6,'Gym Retro','We’re releasing the full version of Gym Retro, a platform for reinforcement learning research on games. This brings our publicly-released game count from around 70 Atari games and 30 Sega games to over 1,000 games across a variety of backing emulators. We’re also releasing the tool we use to add new games to the platform.','https://openai.com/index/gym-retro','','2018-05-25 07:00:00','{\"raw_item\":\"<item>\\n            <title><![CDATA[Gym Retro]]><\\/title>\\n            <description><![CDATA[We\\u2019re releasing the full version of\\u00a0Gym Retro, a platform for reinforcement learning research on games. This brings our publicly-released game count from around 70 Atari games and 30 Sega games to over 1,000 games across a variety of backing emulators. We\\u2019re also releasing the tool we use to add new games to the\\u00a0platform.]]><\\/description>\\n            <link>https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/gym-retro<\\/link>\\n            <guid isPermaLink=\\\"true\\\">https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/gym-retro<\\/guid>\\n            <category><![CDATA[Research]]><\\/category>\\n            <pubDate>Fri, 25 May 2018 07:00:00 GMT<\\/pubDate>\\n        <\\/item>\",\"source_name\":\"OpenAI Blog\"}',33.56,NULL,0.00,0,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'2026-01-31 10:47:37','2026-01-31 10:47:37'),
(772,6,'AI and compute','We’re releasing an analysis showing that since 2012, the amount of compute used in the largest AI training runs has been increasing exponentially with a 3.4-month doubling time (by comparison, Moore’s Law had a 2-year doubling period)[^footnote-correction]. Since 2012, this metric has grown by more than 300,000x (a 2-year doubling period would yield only a 7x increase). Improvements in compute have been a key component of AI progress, so as long as this trend continues, it’s worth preparing for the implications of systems far outside today’s capabilities.','https://openai.com/index/ai-and-compute','','2018-05-16 07:00:00','{\"raw_item\":\"<item>\\n            <title><![CDATA[AI and compute]]><\\/title>\\n            <description><![CDATA[We\\u2019re releasing an analysis showing that since 2012, the amount of compute used in the largest AI training runs has been increasing exponentially with a 3.4-month doubling time (by comparison, Moore\\u2019s Law had a 2-year doubling period)[^footnote-correction]. Since 2012, this metric has grown by more than 300,000x (a 2-year doubling period would yield only a 7x increase). Improvements in compute have been a key component of AI progress, so as long as this trend continues, it\\u2019s worth preparing for the implications of systems far outside today\\u2019s capabilities.]]><\\/description>\\n            <link>https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/ai-and-compute<\\/link>\\n            <guid isPermaLink=\\\"true\\\">https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/ai-and-compute<\\/guid>\\n            <category><![CDATA[Research]]><\\/category>\\n            <pubDate>Wed, 16 May 2018 07:00:00 GMT<\\/pubDate>\\n        <\\/item>\",\"source_name\":\"OpenAI Blog\"}',40.00,NULL,0.00,0,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'2026-01-31 10:47:37','2026-01-31 10:47:37'),
(773,6,'AI safety via debate','We’re proposing an AI safety technique which trains agents to debate topics with one another, using a human to judge who wins.','https://openai.com/index/debate','','2026-01-31 10:58:16','{\"raw_item\":\"<item>\\n            <title><![CDATA[AI safety via debate]]><\\/title>\\n            <description><![CDATA[We\\u2019re proposing an AI safety technique which trains agents to debate topics with one another, using a human to judge who wins.]]><\\/description>\\n            <link>https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/debate<\\/link>\\n            <guid isPermaLink=\\\"true\\\">https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/debate<\\/guid>\\n            <category><![CDATA[Safety & Alignment]]><\\/category>\\n            <pubDate>Thu, 03 May 2018 07:00:00 GMT<\\/pubDate>\\n        <\\/item>\",\"source_name\":\"OpenAI Blog\"}',44.00,NULL,0.00,0,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'2026-01-31 10:47:37','2026-01-31 10:58:16'),
(774,6,'Evolved Policy Gradients','We’re releasing an experimental metalearning approach called Evolved Policy Gradients, a method that evolves the loss function of learning agents, which can enable fast training on novel tasks. Agents trained with EPG can succeed at basic tasks at test time that were outside their training regime, like learning to navigate to an object on a different side of the room from where it was placed during training.','https://openai.com/index/evolved-policy-gradients','','2018-04-18 07:00:00','{\"raw_item\":\"<item>\\n            <title><![CDATA[Evolved Policy Gradients]]><\\/title>\\n            <description><![CDATA[We\\u2019re releasing an experimental metalearning approach called Evolved Policy Gradients, a method that evolves the loss function of learning agents, which can enable fast training on novel tasks. Agents trained with EPG can succeed at basic tasks at test time that were outside their training regime, like learning to navigate to an object on a different side of the room from where it was placed during training.]]><\\/description>\\n            <link>https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/evolved-policy-gradients<\\/link>\\n            <guid isPermaLink=\\\"true\\\">https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/evolved-policy-gradients<\\/guid>\\n            <category><![CDATA[Research]]><\\/category>\\n            <pubDate>Wed, 18 Apr 2018 07:00:00 GMT<\\/pubDate>\\n        <\\/item>\",\"source_name\":\"OpenAI Blog\"}',37.52,NULL,0.00,0,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'2026-01-31 10:47:37','2026-01-31 10:47:37'),
